I'll approach this as **expert-architect-descartes** вҖ” foundational design through systematic doubt, then hand off to **expert-abstractions-liskov** for interface contracts.

---

## Assumptions

| # | Assumption | Confidence | Failure Mode |
|---|-----------|------------|--------------|
| A1 | Users are authenticated before preference reads/writes | High | Unauthorized preference mutation; one user silences another |
| A2 | Channel providers (SMTP, SMS gateway, APNS/FCM) are unreliable | Certain | Dropped notifications, duplicate sends on retry |
| A3 | Notification volume is bursty (deploy alerts, marketing blasts) | High | Queue saturation, rate-limit exhaustion, provider throttling |
| A4 | User-supplied contact data (email, phone) may be invalid or stale | Certain | Silent delivery failure, wasted provider spend |
| A5 | Clock skew exists between services | Medium | Rate-limit windows miscounted, premature or delayed expiry |
| A6 | A single user may have multiple push device tokens | Certain | Fan-out required per push notification |
| A7 | Regulatory constraints (GDPR, TCPA, CAN-SPAM) require opt-in proof and unsubscribe | Certain | Legal liability if consent metadata is lost |

## Failure Modes

| Assumption | Failure | Impact | Fallback |
|-----------|---------|--------|----------|
| A1 | Broken authn/authz | Preference tampering | Enforce ownership check at repository layer; never trust caller-supplied userId without token validation |
| A2 | Provider timeout/5xx | Notification lost | Persistent outbox with at-least-once delivery; idempotency key per notificationГ—channel |
| A3 | Burst exceeds rate limit | Notifications queued indefinitely or dropped | Per-user sliding window + global circuit breaker; priority tiers (transactional > marketing) |
| A4 | Invalid contact data | Silent failure | Verify on write (email verification, phone validation); track delivery failures and auto-disable after N consecutive bounces |
| A5 | Clock skew | Rate window drift | Use monotonic counters in a single rate-limit store (Redis); avoid distributed wall-clock comparisons |
| A6 | Stale device tokens | Push delivery failure | APNS/FCM feedback loop вҶ’ auto-prune invalid tokens |
| A7 | Missing consent proof | Legal exposure | Immutable consent event log; consent is a prerequisite gate, not a filter |

## Fallbacks

Covered above. The critical architectural fallback is the **transactional outbox pattern**: a notification is not "sent" until the provider acknowledges it. Until then, it lives in a durable queue with retry policy.

## Foundation

### Core Types

```typescript
// в”Җв”Җ Identity в”Җв”Җ

type UserId = string & { readonly __brand: "UserId" };
type NotificationId = string & { readonly __brand: "NotificationId" };
type IdempotencyKey = string & { readonly __brand: "IdempotencyKey" };

// в”Җв”Җ Channels в”Җв”Җ

